00:26:43,577 --> 00:26:44,417
Yeah, please do.

556
00:26:45,378 --> 00:26:48,679
So as I listened to your talk, there

557
00:26:48,799 --> 00:26:52,821
is this weird point of communion between our two talks, which

558
00:26:52,961 --> 00:26:56,462
is you want to be clear with prospective players

559
00:26:56,522 --> 00:26:57,442
about what they're going to get.

560
00:26:58,423 --> 00:27:00,763
And that seems like such a simple thing,

561
00:27:01,264 --> 00:27:02,744
but as I was listening to your talk,

562
00:27:02,844 --> 00:27:03,785
I was sort of wondering.

563
00:27:05,246 --> 00:27:07,188
how we actually do that communication.

564
00:27:07,228 --> 00:27:08,910
Because if you think about the critical discourse

565
00:27:08,970 --> 00:27:10,972
around games, like a game is brilliant,

566
00:27:11,032 --> 00:27:12,734
or it's not brilliant, or it's really good,

567
00:27:12,934 --> 00:27:14,716
or it's not good, it's an eight or a 10.

568
00:27:15,476 --> 00:27:17,438
And that doesn't really speak to any of the things

569
00:27:17,478 --> 00:27:19,040
that actually really matter when it comes to

570
00:27:19,080 --> 00:27:22,203
whether or not a person is going to like a game.

571
00:27:22,684 --> 00:27:25,046
And so, you know, as someone who has...

572
00:27:26,157 --> 00:27:28,901
brought games to market and knows that song and dance.

573
00:27:28,941 --> 00:27:31,045
Like, what are the ways that you go about communicating

574
00:27:31,545 --> 00:27:33,228
what you're offering to your players?

575
00:27:34,129 --> 00:27:36,653
And are there things that you try to avoid for that reason

576
00:27:36,713 --> 00:27:38,375
so that they don't get the wrong idea

577
00:27:38,395 --> 00:27:39,537
about the game that you're offering them?

578
00:27:40,359 --> 00:27:45,244
So Cole's question is, what do I do as a designer and publisher

579
00:27:45,604 --> 00:27:47,686
to communicate the possible experience,

580
00:27:47,706 --> 00:27:49,168
the potential experience for players?

581
00:27:49,588 --> 00:27:52,571
And how can I best address it?

582
00:27:52,652 --> 00:27:54,874
And this is so important for publishers, I think.

583
00:27:55,294 --> 00:27:57,256
And there's a bunch of ways you can do this.

584
00:27:58,057 --> 00:28:00,160
Obviously, the artistic style is the first thing.

585
00:28:01,601 --> 00:28:06,647
I've seen games that are about, they have art that's very kid-friendly and the game

586
00:28:06,687 --> 00:28:08,989
turns out to be a two-hour resource management game.

587
00:28:10,030 --> 00:28:12,854
And to me, that's an example of unintended dissonance.

588
00:28:13,855 --> 00:28:15,817
I certainly fell into the trap myself once.

589
00:28:16,818 --> 00:28:20,784
my game Battle Merchants was originally about fighting robots,

590
00:28:21,465 --> 00:28:23,108
about building and selling fighting robots.

591
00:28:23,128 --> 00:28:25,852
You see I did it right there, because I would go to people and say,

592
00:28:25,892 --> 00:28:28,556
hey, do you want to play my game about building and selling fighting robots?

593
00:28:28,877 --> 00:28:31,140
And they would say, sure, I'll play your game about fighting robots.

594
00:28:31,240 --> 00:28:32,342
And you see there's a difference there.

595
00:28:32,753 --> 00:28:34,254
It's a little difference in expectation.

596
00:28:34,955 --> 00:28:36,916
And they would enjoy the game by the second round,

597
00:28:36,936 --> 00:28:38,757
but that first round was all dissonance.

598
00:28:38,897 --> 00:28:39,918
That's not what I expected.

599
00:28:40,338 --> 00:28:43,900
So art, theme, just understanding.

600
00:28:43,940 --> 00:28:45,381
A lot of this is socialized.

601
00:28:45,421 --> 00:28:47,763
It's not like it's an absolute thing.

602
00:28:48,263 --> 00:28:50,745
At some point, we have come to understand

603
00:28:50,785 --> 00:28:53,846
that when we see this very light medieval fantasy theme,

604
00:28:54,587 --> 00:28:56,789
We know that there's gonna be like castle building

605
00:28:56,829 --> 00:28:58,851
and cubes and pigs and that sort of thing,

606
00:28:59,211 --> 00:29:04,576
and brick and some weird ingenious German mechanism

607
00:29:04,616 --> 00:29:08,219
that will somehow convert resources into VP.

608
00:29:09,060 --> 00:29:10,301
And we're okay with that, you know?

609
00:29:10,461 --> 00:29:13,724
And I think while there's a lot of room to innovate,

610
00:29:14,985 --> 00:29:18,007
if you innovate too much or if you're unaware

611
00:29:18,168 --> 00:29:21,150
of this sort of metalanguage that's kind of been built up,

612
00:29:21,790 --> 00:29:26,012
you really do risk this dissonance that can wind up sinking a game.

